<Project>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       FS-GG ORG-SHARED MSBuild PROPERTIES
       Source of truth: FS-GG/.github → dist/dotnet/Directory.Build.props
       Distributed by scripts/sync-build-config.sh. DO NOT EDIT in a consumer repo —
       edits are overwritten on the next sync and fail the drift check (check mode).
       Repo-specific properties (TargetFramework, package metadata, F# warning
       promotions, fsdocs, …) go in Directory.Build.local.props, imported after the
       org defaults so a repo may override any of them (last definition wins). The one
       block deliberately placed AFTER that import is the api-breaking-change-gate: it
       must READ the adopter's $(FsggApiGate), which is set in local.props (H1 fix,
       .github#125 — see its note below).
       Contract: lockfile-restore-enforcement + shared-build-config (registry/dependencies.yml).
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <PropertyGroup Label="Determinism">
    <Deterministic>true</Deterministic>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <PropertyGroup Label="Central Package Management">
    <ManagePackageVersionsCentrally>true</ManagePackageVersionsCentrally>
    <CentralPackageTransitivePinningEnabled>true</CentralPackageTransitivePinningEnabled>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <!-- lock-hash determinism (ADR-0032, .github#473/#471): FSharp.Core resolves from ONE source, so a
       regenerated packages.lock.json is byte-identical on any machine.

       THE DEFECT. The F# SDK injects its OWN bundled copy of FSharp.Core as a restore source:
       Microsoft.FSharp.NetSdk.targets appends $(_FSharpCoreLibraryPacksFolder) —
       …/sdk/<ver>/FSharp/library-packs — to RestoreAdditionalProjectSources, and pins
       FSCorePackageVersion to exactly the version this org references (10.1.301). That copy is a
       DIFFERENT .nupkg than nuget.org serves at the same id+version (3,051,664 B vs 3,066,660 B).
       Nothing was ever re-published and no feed lied — there have always been two packages. A lock
       file's `contentHash` is therefore a function of WHICH SOURCE served the package, and a local
       folder source BEATS nuget.org when both are offered. So CI (no packageSourceMapping) resolved
       library-packs and committed `FwQFuqOA…`, while a dev box whose mapping does not admit
       library-packs resolved nuget.org and produced `excLf2zM…`. Same id, same version, two hashes,
       and whichever machine ran the restore last won the `git diff`.

       WHY IT HAS TO BE FIXED HERE, in MSBuild. The injection arrives via
       RestoreAdditionalProjectSources, NOT as a configured NuGet source, so none of the usual
       hermeticity levers touch it: `<clear/>` in nuget.config does not remove it, a fresh
       NUGET_PACKAGES does not bypass it, and clearing the NuGet http-cache does not either. A
       perfectly COLD restore still resolves the SDK's copy — cold is not hermetic (ADR-0032 §5 still
       stands on its own merits; it just never closed this hole).
       (Note for editors: XML comments cannot contain a double hyphen, so CLI flags are named without
       their leading dashes throughout this comment.)

       THE FIX. DisableImplicitLibraryPacksFolder is the SDK's own opt-out and it guards the
       injection itself, so the folder is REMOVED from the source list rather than deprioritised —
       with it set, a restore that can reach no other source fails NU1101 instead of quietly falling
       back to the SDK copy. FSharp.Core then comes from nuget.org (also the signed copy) everywhere,
       and `contentHash` becomes a function of (id, version) alone — no longer of the SDK patch level.

       THAT CLAIM IS NOW EXECUTED, not just asserted (.github#473 step 3). tests/lockfile-cold/ leg 7
       drives real restores against an empty feed, so the SDK's folder is the only thing that could
       serve FSharp.Core, and checks three things: in the SDK's default state the folder DOES serve it
       (the defect is real, so the test has a subject); with the property set the folder is gone and the
       restore fails NU1101; and a probe that INHERITS THIS FILE gets the same exclusion.

       That last leg is the one guarding the line below. The property is an SDK-INTERNAL condition in
       Microsoft.FSharp.NetSdk.targets, not a documented MSBuild contract, so the SDK may rename it —
       and this file is distributed, so it may also be edited into something that merely LOOKS set. A
       grep could not tell the difference: it passes on a PropertyGroup wrapped in a false Condition,
       on one overridden after the import, and on one commented out with the element still in the
       prose. The fixture restores under the file instead, so anything that makes the property inert —
       however cleverly — puts library-packs back in the source list and reds the leg. Nothing else in
       the org would notice: the sync drift check only proves this file still MATCHES its copies, never
       that it WORKS.

       WHY THAT MATTERS, STATED HONESTLY (.github#536, corrected by #805). This comment used to say it
       mattered "because global.json says rollForward: latestFeature", and was then corrected to say the
       opposite — that four of the five consumers had NO global.json, so there was no floor to reason
       from. BOTH sentences hard-coded a per-repo census, and a census is exactly the thing that rots:
       the second one was false within weeks, once the consumers began adopting the pin (#805).

       So state the part that does NOT rot. `rollForward: latestFeature` means a pin is a FLOOR, not a
       lock: within the pinned major.minor it accepts the HIGHEST feature band and patch installed, so
       10.0.301 is served by whatever 10.0.x the machine happens to have. (It is a floor, not a free
       roll: a machine with only 11.x satisfies nothing and the build fails.) So a pin narrows WHICH
       SDK restores without determining it — two machines honouring the same global.json can still
       restore under different SDKs. An SDK-dependent contentHash is therefore a difference between
       any two machines TODAY, not a risk that materialises the next time somebody bumps the pin.
       Pinned or unpinned, SDK-independence is worth having, and this property is why.

       Do not re-add a census in place of that argument. If you need to know who carries the pin, ASK
       THE REPOS — the answer changes without touching this file, which is the whole problem. The
       FILES note in FS-GG/.github's scripts/sync-build-config.sh carries a loop that measures it.

       The SDK pin is distributed as a managed file (dist/dotnet/global.json, #536) but is NOT in
       sync-build-config's FILES list. Presence in every consumer is NOT sufficient to add it: the
       drift check compares CONTENT, so a consumer naming a different band than the canonical one goes
       red the moment the name lands in that list — which is not hypothetical, it was true of three of
       the five in July 2026. Whether it should EVER be managed is an open decision (.github#903);
       leaving it unmanaged is a live option. Read the ordering note in FS-GG/.github's
       scripts/sync-build-config.sh before you touch that list. (If you are reading this in a consumer
       repo, that script is not here — this file is distributed; its source of truth is FS-GG/.github.)

       ADOPTING THIS IS A ONE-TIME RE-PIN, AND THE ORDER IS LOAD-BEARING. Syncing this file flips the
       source a repo restores from, so its committed `FwQFuqOA…` becomes `excLf2zM…`. Regenerate the
       lock in the SAME PR that syncs this file (a cold `dotnet restore` with force-evaluate). Do NOT
       re-pin a repo ahead of the sync: a lock re-pinned to nuget.org's hash, met by a CI that still
       resolves library-packs, fails locked restore on a CORRECT lock file — which is precisely what
       blocked #429's repair for a day (ADR-0032 §3). -->
  <PropertyGroup Label="lock-hash determinism">
    <DisableImplicitLibraryPacksFolder>true</DisableImplicitLibraryPacksFolder>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <PropertyGroup Label="lockfile-restore-enforcement">
    <!-- Commit packages.lock.json and restore in locked mode in CI so any dependency-graph
         drift (a stale or silently substituted FS.GG.UI.* version, or any transitive bump)
         FAILS restore instead of resolving quietly. -->
    <RestorePackagesWithLockFile>true</RestorePackagesWithLockFile>
    <!-- UNIFIED GATE (H3 / .github#19, ADR-0006): gate on GITHUB_ACTIONS, NOT on
         ContinuousIntegrationBuild. Rationale: some repos (SDD) force CIB=true
         unconditionally for determinism, so a CIB gate fails-closed on a fresh local
         clone; GITHUB_ACTIONS is the real CI signal present in every repo's workflow.
         `And Exists(...lockfile)` lets a first restore bootstrap the lockfile instead
         of blocking, so a brand-new project is never wedged. -->
    <RestoreLockedMode Condition="'$(GITHUB_ACTIONS)' == 'true' And Exists('$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)/packages.lock.json')">true</RestoreLockedMode>
    <!-- Restore-phase NU16xx are not reliably promoted by TreatWarningsAsErrors, so promote
         silent substitution (NU1603) and out-of-range (NU1608) explicitly. -->
    <WarningsAsErrors>$(WarningsAsErrors);NU1603;NU1608</WarningsAsErrors>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <!-- Bootstrap fail-open guard (review low). The RestoreLockedMode condition above deliberately
       `And Exists(...lockfile)` so a first restore can bootstrap a missing lockfile instead of
       wedging a brand-new project. The cost: a repo that NEVER committed packages.lock.json restores
       UNLOCKED in CI with no signal — the lockfile-restore-enforcement gate silently does nothing.
       Surface it as a high-importance MESSAGE (not a Warning: an MSBuild <Warning> is promoted to an
       error under `-warnaserror`/`MSBuildTreatWarningsAsErrors`, which would fail the very first
       bootstrap restore and re-wedge the case this is meant to keep unblocked). Hooked to the single
       restore target CollectPackageReferences so it prints once per restore; the repo closes the hole
       by committing the generated lockfile. -->
  <Target Name="FsggWarnMissingLockfileInCI"
          BeforeTargets="CollectPackageReferences"
          Condition="'$(GITHUB_ACTIONS)' == 'true' And '$(RestorePackagesWithLockFile)' == 'true' And !Exists('$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)/packages.lock.json')">
    <Message Importance="high" Text="[lockfile-restore-enforcement] packages.lock.json is missing in CI (GITHUB_ACTIONS=true) — locked restore is NOT enforced for $(MSBuildProjectName); restore is running UNLOCKED (bootstrap fail-open). Commit the generated packages.lock.json to arm the gate." />
  </Target>

  <!-- Repo-specific overrides. This import sits AFTER the org defaults above (so a consumer can
       override any of them — MSBuild property last-write-wins) and BEFORE the api-breaking-change-gate
       below (so that gate can READ the adopter's $(FsggApiGate), which is set here in local.props).
       H1 (.github#125): MSBuild evaluates PropertyGroup Conditions in document order, so a gate placed
       ABOVE this import would test $(FsggApiGate) before local.props defines it and silently no-op the
       EnablePackageValidation / WarningsNotAsErrors demotion — while its ItemGroup, evaluated in the
       later item pass, would STILL inject the analyzer PackageReference, breaking an adopter's
       TreatWarningsAsErrors build. Placing the whole gate after this import removes that asymmetry. -->
  <Import Project="Directory.Build.local.props" Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)Directory.Build.local.props')" />

  <!-- api-breaking-change-gate (H3 / .github#20, epic #16 Pillar 5): catch accidental public-API
       breaks on packable libraries (FS.GG.Contracts, FS.GG.UI.*) so a break forces a SemVer major,
       which the registry version ranges then enforce.

       OPT-IN and OFF by default (FsggApiGate unset). Turning it on adds a PackageReference, so a
       repo enables it deliberately as an adoption step and regenerates its packages.lock.json then.
       This keeps a plain sync of the shared config non-breaking under locked restore.

       Evaluated AFTER the *.local.props import above so the Condition observes the adopter's
       $(FsggApiGate) (H1 fix, .github#125).

       F# NO-OP (M7 / .github#125; mechanism recorded on the apicompat-publicapi-gate registry row +
       the #20 note): Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.PublicApiAnalyzers is a Roslyn C#/VB source analyzer and
       is a SILENT NO-OP on the org's F# packables (FS.GG.Contracts, FS.GG.UI.*) — the RS00xx
       diagnostics never fire there. On F# projects only the Package Validation / ApiCompat half
       (EnablePackageValidation, below) yields API-break signal; the F# source-surface record stays the
       constitution's committed .fsi signatures + surface/*.surface.txt baselines. Do NOT rely on the
       RS00xx analyzer half to guard an F# public API — it bites on C#/VB packables only.

       Stages (set FsggApiGate in Directory.Build.local.props):
         unset / false  → off.
         advisory / true → on; public-API analyzer diagnostics stay WARNINGS even under the repo's
                           TreatWarningsAsErrors, so adoption never breaks a build. Add the baselines
                           (PublicAPI.Shipped.txt / PublicAPI.Unshipped.txt) per packable project.
         required        → ratchet; the same diagnostics surface as build-breaking errors, and a repo
                           that also sets PackageValidationBaselineVersion gets ApiCompat at pack. -->
  <PropertyGroup Label="api-breaking-change-gate"
                 Condition="'$(FsggApiGate)' != '' And '$(FsggApiGate)' != 'false'">
    <!-- Package Validation = the SDK-integrated ApiCompat: compares the packed output against the
         last published baseline at pack. Dormant until a repo sets PackageValidationBaselineVersion
         (in *.local.props, to its last released version), so enabling it here is harmless. This is the
         ONLY half of the gate that bites on the F# packables (see F# NO-OP above). -->
    <EnablePackageValidation Condition="'$(IsPackable)' != 'false'">true</EnablePackageValidation>
    <!-- Advisory keeps the public-API analyzer diagnostics non-breaking regardless of the repo's
         TreatWarningsAsErrors; FsggApiGate=required drops this demotion so they fail the build.
         RS0016/RS0017 symbol (not) in declared API; RS0022 constructor; RS0024/RS0025/RS0026/RS0027
         shape/overload; RS0036/RS0037 nullability/annotation; RS0041 oblivious API. -->
    <WarningsNotAsErrors Condition="'$(FsggApiGate)' != 'required'">$(WarningsNotAsErrors);RS0016;RS0017;RS0022;RS0024;RS0025;RS0026;RS0027;RS0036;RS0037;RS0041</WarningsNotAsErrors>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup Label="api-breaking-change-gate"
             Condition="'$(FsggApiGate)' != '' And '$(FsggApiGate)' != 'false'">
    <!-- Analyzer-only (PrivateAssets=all): never flows to a package's dependencies. Version is
         centrally pinned in Directory.Packages.props. The analyzer tracks the declared API only when
         both baseline files are present, so an opt-in repo that has not added them yet stays silent
         (run the analyzer's code-fix to generate them). C#/VB only — a no-op on F# (see above). -->
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.PublicApiAnalyzers" PrivateAssets="all" />
    <AdditionalFiles Include="PublicAPI.Shipped.txt"   Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)/PublicAPI.Shipped.txt')" />
    <AdditionalFiles Include="PublicAPI.Unshipped.txt" Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)/PublicAPI.Unshipped.txt')" />
  </ItemGroup>

</Project>
